article.description:
Kevin Garnett helped Minnesota end a
seven-game losing streak, scoring a season-high 37 points in the
Timberwolves' 95-89 victory over the Kings.
article.headline: KG helps Wolves snap seven-game slide
article.linkText: Wolves edge Kings behind KG's season-high 37
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- The Minnesota Timberwolves finally figured out how to finish a game strong. Now they'll try to do the same with their lost season. Kevin Garnett helped Minnesota end a seven-game losing streak, scoring 28 of his season-high 37 points in the second half of the Timberwolves' 95-89 victory over the sloppy Sacramento Kings on Sunday. "A big gorilla off our back," Garnett said after he made 15 of 17 foul shots and grabbed 10 rebounds. Trenton Hassell had 12 points to go with tight defense on Ron Artest, Rashad McCants scored 11 points and Mark Blount added 10 for Minnesota, which nearly let Sacramento steal a victory in the closing seconds but got nine points from Garnett in the last 39 seconds -- seven at the free throw line. Mike Bibby, who has scored at least 29 points in four of his last seven games, led the Kings with 35. "We were just doing stupid stuff," Bibby said. "We didn't shoot the ball very well, either." After going 0-6 on a trip up and down the West Coast in which they held halftime leads in all six games, the Timberwolves turned it around at home against a Kings team fighting for playoff positioning. More importantly, they won a close one. Minnesota has lost 10 times this season when leading after three quarters and is 1-9 in games decided by three points or less. "You lose that many close games, it will shake your confidence," coach Dwane Casey said. Perhaps none more than a 93-91 defeat to Sacramento here three months earlier, when Bonzi Wells hit a 3-pointer at the buzzer. The Wolves were still 12-8 after that, but they never recovered. "That was a turning point in our season," Casey said. "I think it took a little starch out of us." The Kings eventually took a turn from that December day, too, but theirs has been for the better. Kevin Martin added 18 points for Sacramento (33-33), which is tied for seventh place in the Western Conference with the Los Angeles Lakers (34-34). After winning five in a row, though, the Kings dropped their second straight. "It was just one of those games," Artest said. "We'll get it back, though." Artest, who had 13 points, stole the ball for what should've been an easy layup at the 60-second mark with his team trailing by five. But fittingly on a frustrating afternoon, Artest lost the ball for his team's 28th turnover, a season high, after he claimed one of the officials impeded his path. "It hit his foot," Artest said. Garnett swished a jumper on the next possession to make it 88-81. Bibby -- who scored eight of the Kings' final 10 points -- wouldn't let Sacramento quit, though, and his two free throws brought the Kings within 91-87. Artest poked the inbound pass away from Ricky Davis and converted it into an easy layup that cut the lead to two, but after Garnett made another pair of foul shots Bibby's long 3-pointer bounced out and into Garnett's hands. "A lot of it was our own fault," Bibby said. "We've got to make sure we take care of the things we need to take care of." The Wolves (27-39), who have already surpassed last season's loss total of 38, are on their way to their worst finish since 1995-96, Garnett's rookie year. All but eliminated from playoff contention, Minnesota will use the season's final 4½ weeks to give more minutes than usual to players like McCants, Marcus Banks and Eddie Griffin whose roles for the future are still undetermined. The rookie McCants has fulfilled his reputation as a moody, enigmatic performer, but he's also one of the Wolves' most talented and explosive players. He had nine of his points before halftime, including a 22-foot jumper in the final minute that gave Minnesota its biggest lead of the half, 40-33. "I'm trying to create an environment of professionalism, working hard and playing hard," Casey said. The Kings, who have only been going seven deep these days, looked a little tired in the third quarter while the Wolves pulled ahead. Corliss Williamson, who had played in only one of the past nine games, made an appearance for Sacramento and clanked a mid-range jumper before letting Garnett score on him in the lane to cap an ugly sequence. Garnett scored eight straight points for Minnesota to boost its lead to a game-large 11, 61-50, before the Kings rallied behind Bibby and climbed within 67-64 at the end of the quarter.

Game notes
Sacramento's previous season high for turnovers was 21, done twice. The 28 miscues were also the most forced by the Wolves this season and one shy of the franchise record. ... The Kings went 3-for-17 from 3-point range. Bibby was 1-for-8.
